WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:11.000 --> 00:00:12.700
Host: Hi, everybody.

00:00:12.700 --> 00:00:16.467
Welcome to a very exciting
Musicians@Google event,

00:00:16.467 --> 00:00:19.700
and before I’m actually gonna say more,

00:00:19.700 --> 00:00:21.400
I wanna show you this.

00:00:24.734 --> 00:00:57.266
♪ [music playing]

00:00:58.266 --> 00:01:02.700
[applause]

00:01:04.700 --> 00:01:07.333
Hi. I hope I’m gonna make it brief.

00:01:07.333 --> 00:01:09.333
I was thinking about soundtracks.

00:01:09.333 --> 00:01:14.100
The bad soundtrack can make a movie much,
much worse. Mediocre soundtrack—

00:01:14.100 --> 00:01:15.834
you know it’s just gonna be there in
the background.

00:01:15.834 --> 00:01:18.767
A good soundtrack is gonna
make a movie a little bit better.

00:01:18.767 --> 00:01:21.266
A great soundtrack is gonna define
the movie.

00:01:21.266 --> 00:01:24.500
An amazing soundtrack is gonna
define the genre.

00:01:24.500 --> 00:01:25.734
If you really, really like it,

00:01:25.734 --> 00:01:27.633
if you have a really, really
incredible soundtrack

00:01:27.633 --> 00:01:32.066
it’s gonna make you wish your life
is a soundtrack of its own.

00:01:32.066 --> 00:01:36.467
Now when you think about Bear’s Battlestar
Galactica soundtrack it’s really

00:01:36.467 --> 00:01:37.734
in a league of its own

00:01:37.734 --> 00:01:40.734
because, all of the these things aside,

00:01:40.734 --> 00:01:42.500
it actually became a part of the series,

00:01:42.500 --> 00:01:46.967
just integral part of what
Battlestar Gallactica was about.

00:01:46.967 --> 00:01:49.667
And it shattered a couple of fourth walls
in the process

00:01:49.667 --> 00:01:54.700
and I’m sure there were many more people
than me that it left speechless.

00:01:54.700 --> 00:01:57.633
And if you look at
other projects by Bear McCreary

00:01:57.633 --> 00:02:02.000
you know he did the TV show Trauma

00:02:02.000 --> 00:02:07.033
and he incorporated actual helicopters
and ambulances in the soundtrack.

00:02:07.033 --> 00:02:10.867
For Human Target, which is another show
Bear’s scoring right now

00:02:10.867 --> 00:02:16.033
he routinely goes out and, and has
50–, 60–people orchestra

00:02:16.033 --> 00:02:18.667
which is unprecedented for modern TV.

00:02:18.667 --> 00:02:23.300
And the whole story of videogame
Dark Void which is a, Bear just went

00:02:23.300 --> 00:02:25.700
and did the 8-bit version of the tune

00:02:25.700 --> 00:02:30.367
and it kind of started a videogame
of its own.

00:02:30.367 --> 00:02:34.200
Maybe he’ll talk about it a little bit more.

00:02:34.200 --> 00:02:37.433
Bear composes, but he also plays piano,
he plays accordion,

00:02:37.433 --> 00:02:42.367
he actually writes lyrics in all
sorts of different languages,

00:02:42.367 --> 00:02:47.667
and I think I even saw him sing once or twice.

00:02:47.667 --> 00:02:51.367
But whatever he does he approaches with so much
enthusiasm and passion

00:02:51.367 --> 00:02:55.533
that I think we are all very lucky
to have him here,

00:02:55.533 --> 00:02:57.333
talk about what he does;

00:02:57.333 --> 00:03:01.834
and maybe play something
if we can convince him to.

00:03:01.834 --> 00:03:04.133
And this is where my original introduction ends,

00:03:04.133 --> 00:03:07.800
but we’re actually really, really lucky
because we also have Raya Yarbrough,

00:03:07.800 --> 00:03:10.100
I don’t know where she is there,

00:03:10.100 --> 00:03:12.000
who’s an incredibly talented vocalist.

00:03:12.000 --> 00:03:14.300
And you think you don’t know her,

00:03:14.300 --> 00:03:17.834
but if we can convince her to sing with Bear

00:03:17.834 --> 00:03:21.266
you will kind of quickly realize where
do you know that gorgeous voice from.

00:03:21.266 --> 00:03:26.700
So that’s the end of my thing here.

00:03:26.700 --> 00:03:29.066
Please give it up for 
Bear McCreary and Raya Yarbrough.

00:03:29.066 --> 00:03:38.200
[applause]

00:03:38.200 --> 00:03:40.166
Bear McCreary: Thank you, thank you.

00:03:40.166 --> 00:03:42.333
That was a pretty cool introduction.

00:03:42.333 --> 00:03:46.500
I don’t know how to follow that exactly.

00:03:46.500 --> 00:03:48.300
This is Raya Yarbrough.

00:03:48.300 --> 00:03:54.900
[applause]

00:03:54.900 --> 00:04:00.233
So what we’re gonna,
before we do anything else-

00:04:00.233 --> 00:04:01.266
Raya Yarbrough: Wanna, like, get you started.

00:04:01.266 --> 00:04:03.600
Bear: Yeah. You were,
you were gonna ask me some things.

00:04:03.600 --> 00:04:05.000
Raya: Okay.

00:04:11.000 --> 00:04:14.000
There’s a lot stuff that Bear did before
Battlestar Galactica, so—

00:04:15.000 --> 00:04:17.000
Why don’t we begin at the beginning.

00:04:18.000 --> 00:04:20.000
Bear: Grab the mike.

00:04:24.567 --> 00:04:27.400
Raya: Is this on?
Oh, it did it by itself.

00:04:27.400 --> 00:04:30.200
It’s the magic of Google.

00:04:30.200 --> 00:04:33.667
Okay, so I guess I’ll just,
oh, you’re miked, so you’re all good.

00:04:33.667 --> 00:04:37.934
So why don’t you tell the good
people how you started off in music,

00:04:37.934 --> 00:04:39.266
when you started, how.

00:04:39.266 --> 00:04:43.100
Bear: Well,

00:04:43.100 --> 00:04:44.800
you were,

00:04:44.800 --> 00:04:49.633
you were clever enough to include
the Megaman clip in there.

00:04:49.633 --> 00:04:55.934
Actually, 8-bit videogames were part of
the first musical experience I ever had.

00:04:55.934 --> 00:05:01.367
And the combination of videogames
and movies and TV that I grew up on,

00:05:01.367 --> 00:05:04.467
is what inspired me to become a musician.

00:05:04.467 --> 00:05:10.433
And as I was growing up, I listened
to nothing but movie music.

00:05:10.433 --> 00:05:16.934
It’s all I ever wanted to do and really
I never considered for a moment

00:05:16.934 --> 00:05:18.767
that I would do anything else.

00:05:18.767 --> 00:05:23.800
So I’m really lucky that it kind of worked
out because I didn’t have a backup plan.

00:05:23.800 --> 00:05:28.600
And so I started—

00:05:28.600 --> 00:05:32.934
I started writing my own music
when I was about, I don’t know, maybe ten;

00:05:32.934 --> 00:05:36.667
and I sucked; I was not working.

00:05:36.667 --> 00:05:41.600
But I just kept trying and I kept trying
and I kept listening to the pieces of music

00:05:41.600 --> 00:05:44.400
that I was really responding to,

00:05:44.400 --> 00:05:48.200
and, I don’t know, somewhere
in high school I started—

00:05:48.200 --> 00:05:50.600
I started to kind of figure
a few things out.

00:05:50.600 --> 00:05:56.367
And I started scoring little movies that
I was making and my friends were making

00:05:56.367 --> 00:06:01.333
and trying to see if I could connect
music that I heard in my head

00:06:01.333 --> 00:06:05.166
with the pictures that I was,
the pictures that I was dealing with,

00:06:05.166 --> 00:06:06.600
and the images that I was dealing with.

00:06:06.600 --> 00:06:09.900
And the answer was – no, I couldn’t,
at first.

00:06:09.900 --> 00:06:12.867
But then I did it again and
I kept working at it,

00:06:12.867 --> 00:06:16.767
and finally started to kind of find some,

00:06:16.767 --> 00:06:20.333
I don’t know, I don’t wanna say
my own kind of inner voice,

00:06:20.333 --> 00:06:24.000
but I did find some things that I
was able to do and gravitate towards.

00:06:24.000 --> 00:06:25.633
And then I,

00:06:25.633 --> 00:06:28.400
so then I ended up the 
USC Thornton School of Music

00:06:28.400 --> 00:06:32.233
where I actually learned how to
do music on a more formal level.

00:06:32.233 --> 00:06:35.467
I didn’t have a lot of training up
until that point except for—

00:06:35.467 --> 00:06:39.100
I studied classical piano for many years.

00:06:39.100 --> 00:06:45.867
But that was sort of my musical
education was formalized there,

00:06:45.867 --> 00:06:49.467
but it really started 
by watching a bunch of movies

00:06:49.467 --> 00:06:52.000
and playing videogames
more than anything else.

00:06:52.000 --> 00:06:54.033
Raya: Yeah. I think,
and if I can weigh in here just

00:06:54.033 --> 00:06:56.500
’cause I’ve happen to know you sort of well,

00:06:56.500 --> 00:07:01.567
as your music has developed through all the
films and TV shows and things you’ve done,

00:07:01.567 --> 00:07:04.467
you’ve, I’ve heard you saying
that you reflected back

00:07:04.467 --> 00:07:07.166
to music that your wrote when you were 15 or 16,

00:07:07.166 --> 00:07:08.967
and you realized, “you know, I kind
of did have a voice, even then.”

00:07:08.967 --> 00:07:11.300
Bear: Yeah. That’s funny
I can find pieces when,

00:07:11.300 --> 00:07:13.100
that I wrote in high school

00:07:13.100 --> 00:07:17.767
and there’s a piece actually,
when I wrote the big theme for Dark Void

00:07:17.767 --> 00:07:20.734
I played it for a buddy of mine and he’s
like, “You wrote that in high school.”

00:07:20.734 --> 00:07:21.734
I’m like, “What are you talkin’ about?”

00:07:21.734 --> 00:07:23.667
And he goes, “You know that one thing?”
and I went back and thought about it

00:07:23.667 --> 00:07:25.834
and I went back to actually go and listen to it
and was like, “Oh, yeah.”

00:07:25.834 --> 00:07:29.533
I mean it’s not as good,
but there was like all these little,

00:07:29.533 --> 00:07:32.333
these little things that I was kind
of stumbling upon in high school

00:07:32.333 --> 00:07:35.100
and then when I got this Dark Void
videogame I was able to kind of

00:07:35.100 --> 00:07:37.900
draw on all these different influences.

00:07:37.900 --> 00:07:40.900
And there’s pieces I wrote that
sound kind of like Battlestar, I mean,

00:07:40.900 --> 00:07:42.133
other things that I’ve done.

00:07:42.133 --> 00:07:45.266
Raya: And listening to your older
music and to music that you’re doing

00:07:45.266 --> 00:07:46.667
like right now, it’s funny,

00:07:46.667 --> 00:07:49.266
it’s almost like from your high school time

00:07:49.266 --> 00:07:51.700
it was the seed and it grew into
this forest

00:07:51.700 --> 00:07:53.633
which was Battlestar Galactica and everything.

00:07:53.633 --> 00:07:56.834
And now it’s almost like you’re kind of
harkening back to some of your original–

00:07:56.834 --> 00:07:59.333
could you talk about some of
your original inspirations,

00:07:59.333 --> 00:08:01.667
some of the people who influenced you
from way, way back–

00:08:01.667 --> 00:08:06.333
Bear: The first film score
that I noticed was

00:08:06.333 --> 00:08:08.166
Back To The Future by Alan Silvestri.

00:08:08.166 --> 00:08:10.033
Anybody remember that score?

00:08:10.033 --> 00:08:10.633
Yeah.

00:08:10.633 --> 00:08:12.700
Raya: Somebody saying—
Bear: That one.

00:08:12.700 --> 00:08:14.266
No, it’s weird.
I talk to people and they are like,

00:08:14.266 --> 00:08:16.100
they’ve never even heard of the movie sometimes.

00:08:16.100 --> 00:08:17.734
It’s just one of those franchises.
[laughter]

00:08:17.734 --> 00:08:20.900
I know. That’s when I was like,
“I feel old.”

00:08:20.900 --> 00:08:23.433
You can talk to a perfectly formed
human being who was born

00:08:23.433 --> 00:08:27.133
after Back To The Future 3 came out.

00:08:27.133 --> 00:08:30.200
So, yeah, it’s weird.

00:08:30.200 --> 00:08:33.133
That was one of the first ones
that caught my ear.

00:08:33.133 --> 00:08:36.834
And, simultaneously, it was the same year,

00:08:36.834 --> 00:08:41.166
Pee-wee’s Big Adventure by Danny Elfman
really struck a chord with me

00:08:41.166 --> 00:08:45.633
and that was – starting after that
point my parents would notice that

00:08:45.633 --> 00:08:47.467
any time that I went and saw a movie,

00:08:47.467 --> 00:08:50.867
I would identify the composer within the
first five or ten seconds of the movie.

00:08:50.867 --> 00:08:53.734
And I was six, seven, eight years old.

00:08:53.734 --> 00:08:56.633
And then the credits would come up
and they’re like, “God damn, he’s right.”

00:08:56.633 --> 00:09:01.367
And so they kind of knew, they could
kind of see where I was going.

00:09:01.367 --> 00:09:07.433
Then in, I also, as a kid, really loved
the music of John Williams.

00:09:07.433 --> 00:09:13.266
Temple Of Doom and Empire Strikes Back
had a big impression on me for sure.

00:09:13.266 --> 00:09:16.233
And then it was in
high school that I discovered–

00:09:16.233 --> 00:09:18.400
I had this sort of epiphany

00:09:18.400 --> 00:09:23.567
when I discovered the film music of
Jerry Goldsmith, Elmer Bernstein,

00:09:23.567 --> 00:09:27.200
Bernard Herrmann, Nino Rota and Ennio Morricone.

00:09:27.200 --> 00:09:30.633
I think of these five guys as the people that I,

00:09:30.633 --> 00:09:32.633
I’m influenced by the most,
and the reason I say that is

00:09:32.633 --> 00:09:37.300
that I realize that everybody that
I adored was borrowing from them.

00:09:37.300 --> 00:09:40.200
And I would go and discover
these scores from the 50s

00:09:40.200 --> 00:09:42.533
that sounded like the scores
from the late 80s and 90s

00:09:42.533 --> 00:09:44.300
that I was falling in love with.

00:09:44.300 --> 00:09:47.000
Not in a bad way, I mean,

00:09:47.000 --> 00:09:50.500
just the influence was there
and that they were innovating,

00:09:50.500 --> 00:09:53.400
I mean stuff like Herrmann’s
The Day The Earth Stood Still

00:09:53.400 --> 00:09:55.767
or Elmer Bernstein’s 
To Kill A Mockingbird,

00:09:55.767 --> 00:09:58.333
which if you put that
in a movie trailer today,

00:09:58.333 --> 00:10:02.367
I don’t think anyone would think
that that music was 55 years old.

00:10:02.367 --> 00:10:06.867
So it’s, that was
a big sort of epiphany for me

00:10:06.867 --> 00:10:09.233
when I realized how far back
this tradition goes

00:10:09.233 --> 00:10:14.300
and started studying very closely
what those guys were doing.

00:10:14.300 --> 00:10:16.233
Raya: Can you say
a little about Elmer?

00:10:16.233 --> 00:10:18.500
Bear: I can.

00:10:18.500 --> 00:10:19.834
I knew Elmer,

00:10:19.834 --> 00:10:22.900
I met him when I was in high school and—

00:10:22.900 --> 00:10:23.867
Raya: It’s Elmer Bernstein.
Bear: Yeah.

00:10:23.867 --> 00:10:30.266
Elmer Bernstein who, who did so many
of the most important film scores

00:10:30.266 --> 00:10:31.600
to ever be written;

00:10:31.600 --> 00:10:33.500
The Ten Commandments,
The Great Escape,

00:10:33.500 --> 00:10:34.400
To Kill A Mockingbird,

00:10:34.400 --> 00:10:35.066
The Magnificent Seven,

00:10:35.066 --> 00:10:37.000
Animal House,
Ghost Busters,

00:10:37.000 --> 00:10:38.767
the list goes on and on.

00:10:38.767 --> 00:10:42.333
I met him when I was in high school
and I played him a bunch of my music

00:10:42.333 --> 00:10:48.500
’cause we had a mutual friend through
this weirdest coincidence in the world.

00:10:48.500 --> 00:10:52.734
And he was really impressed with,

00:10:52.734 --> 00:10:56.533
I think the energy that I had,
and the amount of stuff I was writing

00:10:56.533 --> 00:10:58.567
and he asked if I was formally trained,

00:10:58.567 --> 00:11:01.767
although I’m sure in hindsight
he knew that I wasn’t.

00:11:01.767 --> 00:11:06.066
And he really kind of took me
under his wing.

00:11:06.066 --> 00:11:09.967
And when I came down to
Los Angeles to go to school,

00:11:09.967 --> 00:11:13.100
I started working for him and one of the,

00:11:13.100 --> 00:11:17.533
no, I guess the first professional
job I ever had was at his,

00:11:17.533 --> 00:11:19.934
at his, at his house,

00:11:19.934 --> 00:11:21.000
his estate.

00:11:21.000 --> 00:11:22.834
And he was gone for the summer and he goes,

00:11:22.834 --> 00:11:25.100
“Hey, like, can you housesit
the place

00:11:25.100 --> 00:11:27.133
and then I’ll give
you a film to orchestrate over the summer.”

00:11:27.133 --> 00:11:30.333
And I was like—
[laughter]

00:11:30.333 --> 00:11:32.900
“Yeah, let me check my schedule.” You know.

00:11:32.900 --> 00:11:34.400
So actually a quick side story.

00:11:34.400 --> 00:11:36.133
I was, I had to,

00:11:36.133 --> 00:11:38.000
I had to dog sit—
he had these dogs—

00:11:38.000 --> 00:11:40.333
and you had to give them these pills
and stuff, and I’m like, “Alright, sure.”

00:11:40.333 --> 00:11:43.500
I did not tell him that since I was
a kid I had this phobia of dogs,

00:11:43.500 --> 00:11:45.500
’cause when I was a little
kid I got attacked by a dog.

00:11:45.500 --> 00:11:47.433
And I was like, “Alright, I just,
I just gotta get over this.

00:11:47.433 --> 00:11:50.266
How big can this dog be?”
Irish Wolfhound. Okay. [laughter]

00:11:50.266 --> 00:11:53.233
It is this big,
I mean on all fours.

00:11:53.233 --> 00:11:54.467
It comes up to here on me.

00:11:54.467 --> 00:11:56.934
And in fact,
when it was a puppy they,

00:11:56.934 --> 00:11:58.233
they had to put it on downers

00:11:58.233 --> 00:12:02.133
because it would jump up on Elmer
and it’s like eight feet high.

00:12:02.133 --> 00:12:04.333
So I get over there and I
see this dog and it was like,

00:12:04.333 --> 00:12:05.934
“Okay. Let’s…”

00:12:05.934 --> 00:12:11.066
My dog, my fear of dogs is of course
non-existent anymore after that summer.

00:12:11.066 --> 00:12:17.000
Anyway, so that was a huge influence
on me because I spent the whole summer

00:12:17.000 --> 00:12:19.467
re-orchestrating a film score
called Kings Of The Sun.

00:12:19.467 --> 00:12:22.266
This was a movie starring Yul
Brynner that came out in 1968.

00:12:22.266 --> 00:12:24.600
I think it’s on DVD,
no, it is on DVD now.

00:12:24.600 --> 00:12:26.900
At the time it wasn’t on DVD,
it wasn’t on TV,

00:12:26.900 --> 00:12:27.934
it wasn’t screened anywhere,

00:12:27.934 --> 00:12:30.600
it had had a theatrical run
and that was it.

00:12:30.600 --> 00:12:35.400
And it was still one of the most highly
sought-after scores that Elmer had written.

00:12:35.400 --> 00:12:36.700
Fans were writing him and saying,

00:12:36.700 --> 00:12:37.834
“Oh, when are you gonna perform
that music?

00:12:37.834 --> 00:12:39.934
Is it gonna be on a soundtrack album?”

00:12:39.934 --> 00:12:41.633
And the recordings had been destroyed,

00:12:41.633 --> 00:12:42.700
the scores had been destroyed,

00:12:42.700 --> 00:12:46.400
because at that point in time
the studio would keep everything.

00:12:46.400 --> 00:12:49.033
And in fact he would tell me stories of
sometimes he’d go to music departments

00:12:49.033 --> 00:12:53.233
to meet a director and he would look at
someone’s writing on a scrap of paper like,

00:12:53.233 --> 00:12:56.233
just notes, they have a stack of old
scrap paper and you’d flip it over

00:12:56.233 --> 00:12:59.567
and it’s a handwritten Jerry Goldsmith
score from like the late 70s.

00:12:59.567 --> 00:13:00.900
It was “Oh, there it is.”

00:13:00.900 --> 00:13:05.633
But anyway, so who knows where his
score is now somebody’s laundry list or,

00:13:05.633 --> 00:13:07.867
or grocery list or something.

00:13:07.867 --> 00:13:10.033
So I re-orchestrated this whole film.

00:13:10.033 --> 00:13:11.433
So I spent the summer,

00:13:11.433 --> 00:13:15.800
he had his handwritten sketches
were literally all that remained—

00:13:15.800 --> 00:13:20.200
and so I was able to go through
and recreate the orchestration

00:13:20.200 --> 00:13:22.667
and I didn’t have a recording
or anything to go by.

00:13:22.667 --> 00:13:28.066
And that taught me more than any program, any class,

00:13:28.066 --> 00:13:29.266
any teacher could have ever taught me,

00:13:29.266 --> 00:13:35.000
because I was just was able to see
exactly how the germs of the ideas

00:13:35.000 --> 00:13:36.266
became this finished score.

00:13:36.266 --> 00:13:38.467
And in fact,

00:13:38.467 --> 00:13:40.433
one of the other things that
I did for him was,

00:13:40.433 --> 00:13:43.367
was, I sort of organized his
whole closet full of archives

00:13:43.367 --> 00:13:49.166
which is now in a collection
at the USC Music Library.

00:13:49.166 --> 00:13:51.467
But at the time it was just
a closet full of stuff,

00:13:51.467 --> 00:13:53.233
and I was going through it with him

00:13:53.233 --> 00:13:55.133
and there were all these things
that he didn’t wanna keep.

00:13:55.133 --> 00:13:56.967
He was just gonna, he’s like,
“No. Throw all that stuff out.”

00:13:56.967 --> 00:13:59.467
And I said, “I can’t,

00:13:59.467 --> 00:14:01.233
I don’t know why, but I can’t
throw this out.”

00:14:01.233 --> 00:14:04.233
It’s like a stack of parts
from the day they recorded

00:14:04.233 --> 00:14:06.500
the cues on To Kill A Mockingbird.

00:14:06.500 --> 00:14:07.533
He was gonna throw them out.

00:14:07.533 --> 00:14:09.734
These are the actual parts
that the musicians read from.

00:14:09.734 --> 00:14:11.734
They’re in my closet now and
I don’t know what to do with them,

00:14:11.734 --> 00:14:14.066
but I was like 
“Do you mind if I keep these?”

00:14:14.066 --> 00:14:16.266
And one of the things that he was
gonna throw out that’s on my wall

00:14:16.266 --> 00:14:19.600
that I look at every day
is a handwritten sketch

00:14:19.600 --> 00:14:21.834
of the main title in The Great Escape.

00:14:21.834 --> 00:14:27.133
And you can see how he thought
of it and before he wrote this,

00:14:27.133 --> 00:14:29.433
that melody didn’t exist.

00:14:29.433 --> 00:14:31.166
I mean like,
I’ll play it real quick.

00:14:31.166 --> 00:14:32.967
I mean this kind of blows,
blows my mind, right?

00:14:32.967 --> 00:14:34.767
That he wrote this—

00:14:34.767 --> 00:14:46.133
♪ [playing upbeat piano]

00:14:46.133 --> 00:14:47.734
I mean, everybody knows this tune, right?

00:14:47.734 --> 00:14:50.467
I mean you think it’s like
an old American folk tune.

00:14:50.467 --> 00:14:51.133
But he wrote it.

00:14:51.133 --> 00:14:56.500
And, I just thought before this piece of
paper existed that song did not exist.

00:14:56.500 --> 00:14:58.667
And when he was gonna throw
that out I was just like,

00:14:58.667 --> 00:15:01.433
“No, no way, can I, I gotta,
I gotta keep this.”

00:15:01.433 --> 00:15:06.100
And so he had a great impact
on me creatively,

00:15:06.100 --> 00:15:08.667
professionally,
but also personally because I,

00:15:08.667 --> 00:15:10.400
I got to spend so much time with him

00:15:10.400 --> 00:15:16.767
and, see that it is possible to
be successful in the movie business

00:15:16.767 --> 00:15:19.934
and the music business, and not
turn out to be a big asshole.

00:15:19.934 --> 00:15:23.567
[laughter] So that was, that
was an eye opener for sure.

00:15:23.567 --> 00:15:26.400
Raya: So in the steps
of not becoming a big asshole,

00:15:26.400 --> 00:15:27.367
shortly after that—

00:15:27.367 --> 00:15:28.333
Bear: Oh, I am a big asshole.

00:15:28.333 --> 00:15:29.467
I failed at that. [laughter]

00:15:29.467 --> 00:15:31.033
Raya: Well, but you grew into it.

00:15:31.033 --> 00:15:31.433
Bear: Yeah, so—

00:15:31.433 --> 00:15:33.667
Raya: Of course the four
seasons of Battlestar Gallactica.

00:15:33.667 --> 00:15:34.400
Bear: Yes.

00:15:34.400 --> 00:15:37.934
Raya: So, so let’s,
let’s talk about this.

00:15:37.934 --> 00:15:39.533
Bear: Um…
Raya: How did you,

00:15:39.533 --> 00:15:41.934
how did you get into Battlestar
and, yeah.

00:15:41.934 --> 00:15:47.767
Bear: Battlestar
was my first job out of school.

00:15:47.767 --> 00:15:49.166
I, I got it,

00:15:49.166 --> 00:15:50.533
the first job that I got,

00:15:50.533 --> 00:15:52.633
I was,

00:15:52.633 --> 00:15:53.667
I graduated,

00:15:53.667 --> 00:15:55.166
I had nothing going on,

00:15:55.166 --> 00:15:57.166
I was actually even,

00:15:57.166 --> 00:16:01.934
I crashed at Elmer’s place, at his
Santa Monica house, for a month.

00:16:01.934 --> 00:16:05.433
So I could score a student film
with a budget of zero dollars.

00:16:05.433 --> 00:16:07.100
But I said, it was like,
“I gotta finish this movie.”

00:16:07.100 --> 00:16:10.800
So I was like literally about to go

00:16:10.800 --> 00:16:12.867
hand in applications at grocery stores
and video stores—

00:16:12.867 --> 00:16:13.834
Raya: There was florist store—

00:16:13.834 --> 00:16:16.433
Bear: Florist. Yeah, florist,
I could have done that.

00:16:16.433 --> 00:16:18.033
Raya: He makes
brilliant flower arrangements.

00:16:18.033 --> 00:16:18.767
Bear: I could have been a florist.

00:16:18.767 --> 00:16:20.133
Raya: If you like his music,
you should see…

00:16:20.133 --> 00:16:20.700
Bear: Yeah.

00:16:20.700 --> 00:16:22.500
Raya: …his flower arrangements.
[laughter]

00:16:22.500 --> 00:16:26.166
Bear: But I got a job
working for Richard Gibbs.

00:16:26.166 --> 00:16:28.266
Richard Gibbs is a film composer

00:16:28.266 --> 00:16:31.667
and former keyboardist
of Oingo Boingo

00:16:31.667 --> 00:16:35.967
which is another story for later on, I guess.

00:16:35.967 --> 00:16:38.734
And, so I got a job working for him

00:16:38.734 --> 00:16:41.967
and I was his assistant.

00:16:41.967 --> 00:16:43.233
I kept the studio running.

00:16:43.233 --> 00:16:47.934
I converted all his computers
to the new sampling software

00:16:47.934 --> 00:16:51.500
which has since become a dinosaur
and I’m the only one who uses it now.

00:16:51.500 --> 00:16:53.667
But at the time, it was new.

00:16:53.667 --> 00:16:57.700
And I also wrote a bunch of cues
and worked with the producers

00:16:57.700 --> 00:17:00.233
and helped him meet his deadlines.

00:17:00.233 --> 00:17:02.533
And he,

00:17:02.533 --> 00:17:05.367
so I worked there about a year,
and at the end of that year

00:17:05.367 --> 00:17:08.667
he landed the Battlestar Galactica mini-series.

00:17:08.667 --> 00:17:13.700
So he asked me to come on board
and help him finish this pilot,

00:17:13.700 --> 00:17:16.567
it was essentially a backdoor pilot.

00:17:16.567 --> 00:17:19.967
And we had to write three,

00:17:19.967 --> 00:17:23.900
almost three hours of music, maybe two and
a half hours of music, in about 14 days.

00:17:23.900 --> 00:17:26.800
So it was an incredible turnaround 
and on top of that,

00:17:26.800 --> 00:17:31.700
the producer had this really
wacky idea of using taiko drums

00:17:31.700 --> 00:17:34.166
and that was kind of all that he said.
He was like, “We like taiko drums.”

00:17:34.166 --> 00:17:34.867
[laughter]

00:17:34.867 --> 00:17:38.033
And I was like, “Okay. I don’t know
what that means.”

00:17:38.033 --> 00:17:42.700
And so actually in that creative process,

00:17:42.700 --> 00:17:48.033
I worked very closely with Richard
and also with,

00:17:48.033 --> 00:17:49.233
with the director Michael Rymer,

00:17:49.233 --> 00:17:51.867
and so when we got through the mini-series,

00:17:51.867 --> 00:17:55.500
and we did use a hefty amount
of taiko drums.

00:17:55.500 --> 00:17:57.800
But also a lot of,

00:17:57.800 --> 00:17:59.767
there was a lot of orchestral writing and,

00:17:59.767 --> 00:18:04.900
and a very sort of ambient non-thematic approach.

00:18:04.900 --> 00:18:08.100
And this was because the producers
felt very strongly

00:18:08.100 --> 00:18:14.000
that they didn’t want the kind of Star Wars
or Star Trek approach to their mini-series.

00:18:14.000 --> 00:18:15.633
In fact,

00:18:15.633 --> 00:18:20.100
if you think about it in comparing the new,
the mini-series to the old show,

00:18:20.100 --> 00:18:23.166
the thing that is the most
different is the music.

00:18:23.166 --> 00:18:24.300
I think more than anything else.

00:18:24.300 --> 00:18:27.066
it’s the one part of the old
show that was completely,

00:18:27.066 --> 00:18:30.433
well, except for the Casino Planet,
that was dropped too. [laughter]

00:18:30.433 --> 00:18:32.633
Alright. So there were two things:
the music and the Casino Planet.

00:18:32.633 --> 00:18:33.900
Raya: Boxey,
don’t forget about Boxey.

00:18:33.900 --> 00:18:34.967
Bear: We had Boxey in the pilot.

00:18:34.967 --> 00:18:36.200
Raya: You did?
Bear: We did.

00:18:36.200 --> 00:18:38.300
And in season one they dropped him on his ass.

00:18:38.300 --> 00:18:39.867
Raya: That’s right.
[laughs]

00:18:39.867 --> 00:18:41.266
Bear: But yeah, he
was there briefly.

00:18:41.266 --> 00:18:43.734
It was the dagget
that was also missing.

00:18:43.734 --> 00:18:44.700
Alright, there
were a few things missing.

00:18:44.700 --> 00:18:47.633
Raya: There was
a dagget at one point, remember?

00:18:47.633 --> 00:18:48.300
Bear: Oh, yeah.

00:18:48.300 --> 00:18:49.633
Raya: Yeah. I don’t know
what scene it is,

00:18:49.633 --> 00:18:52.500
but if you look at one scene you can see
a dagget flying out of the airlock.

00:18:52.500 --> 00:18:54.266
Bear: Yeah. It’s true.
There is a dagget and—

00:18:54.266 --> 00:18:58.000
And, I think the Starship Enterprise
and the Millennium Falcon

00:18:58.000 --> 00:18:59.433
are in the fleet in a couple of shots.

00:18:59.433 --> 00:19:01.066
Raya: Oh, that’s right.
[laughter]

00:19:01.066 --> 00:19:03.667
Bear: Yeah. A bunch of nerds
worked on the show. [laughter]

00:19:03.667 --> 00:19:09.600
So, but anyway, so long,
long story medium-long,

00:19:09.600 --> 00:19:15.734
the pilot is relatively
successful and it goes to series.

00:19:15.734 --> 00:19:21.166
And at that point Richard needs
to go on to feature films.

00:19:21.166 --> 00:19:24.934
He’s got his slate is full with feature
films and he can’t take on a weekly series

00:19:24.934 --> 00:19:28.567
that would require the amount of
original music that Battlestar required.

00:19:28.567 --> 00:19:33.066
So, of course, the producers
didn’t wanna hire me at all.

00:19:33.066 --> 00:19:37.200
And while they were off
looking for other people,

00:19:37.200 --> 00:19:40.233
there was one deadline coming up
which was for this episode “33,”

00:19:40.233 --> 00:19:42.133
which was the first episode aired.

00:19:42.133 --> 00:19:43.734
So they go, “Alright, well, you can take,

00:19:43.734 --> 00:19:47.266
you can do this while we’re
off looking for somebody else.”

00:19:47.266 --> 00:19:49.600
And so I did it.

00:19:49.600 --> 00:19:54.867
I did the hell out of it and
really gave it my all and,

00:19:54.867 --> 00:19:58.033
and brought in all the musicians
that I wanted to bring in.

00:19:58.033 --> 00:20:01.133
All of whom stayed on ’til the end.

00:20:01.133 --> 00:20:05.100
That episode planted the seeds
thematically that would go all the way

00:20:05.100 --> 00:20:06.734
to the last episode.

00:20:06.734 --> 00:20:07.867
But I didn’t know any better
at the time.

00:20:07.867 --> 00:20:10.700
I mean, I was just,
I was just trying to,

00:20:10.700 --> 00:20:12.033
I don’t even wanna say I
was trying to keep the job,

00:20:12.033 --> 00:20:16.100
I was just trying to do an excellent job
because I really adored that episode.

00:20:16.100 --> 00:20:19.066
I mean I thought it was
so gripping and powerful

00:20:19.066 --> 00:20:21.700
and a worthy follow-up
of the mini-series.

00:20:21.700 --> 00:20:26.600
And after the playback the producers
invited me to come look at the next episode.

00:20:26.600 --> 00:20:30.266
And I thought, “Okay. We’re doing
two episodes of Battlestar.”

00:20:30.266 --> 00:20:33.900
So that feeling of waiting for,
I can get fired tomorrow, though,

00:20:33.900 --> 00:20:38.600
that went away about halfway
through season four. [laughter]

00:20:38.600 --> 00:20:40.233
That’s when I started,
when I was like,

00:20:40.233 --> 00:20:42.800
“You know, I probably am gonna finish this show.

00:20:42.800 --> 00:20:46.166
I think, I think I’m gonna stick around.”

00:20:46.166 --> 00:20:47.300
But that’s it.

00:20:47.300 --> 00:20:49.400
I was,

00:20:49.400 --> 00:20:54.200
I had just turned 24 when I became
the composer of Battlestar Galactica

00:20:54.200 --> 00:20:56.700
and it was, it was really through—

00:20:56.700 --> 00:20:58.900
Raya: How did you feel starting
your career so late? [laughter]

00:20:58.900 --> 00:21:01.834
Bear: Yeah, I know.
I know. [laughter]

00:21:01.834 --> 00:21:02.767
It was tough.

00:21:02.767 --> 00:21:04.633
It was tough.

00:21:04.633 --> 00:21:06.100
Well, seriously when I was 15, I was like,

00:21:06.100 --> 00:21:08.133
“I’m gonna be famous by the time I’m 20.

00:21:08.133 --> 00:21:09.400
I’ll just land a big movie.”

00:21:09.400 --> 00:21:12.633
The funny thing is when I was,
when I was a kid I never wanted to do TV.

00:21:12.633 --> 00:21:14.100
I wanted to do movies.

00:21:14.100 --> 00:21:21.200
And ironically the creative freedom
that I have found in television,

00:21:21.200 --> 00:21:24.166
and I find that the quality
in television

00:21:24.166 --> 00:21:26.934
surpasses most of what comes out
in theaters,

00:21:26.934 --> 00:21:30.433
and I think about all the big summer action
blockbusters that come out and I go,

00:21:30.433 --> 00:21:32.033
“Well, this would be cool if I did that,”

00:21:32.033 --> 00:21:35.433
but would I have traded four years
of Battlestar, you know?

00:21:35.433 --> 00:21:37.400
Raya: Actually that,
that leads me, blah, blah,

00:21:37.400 --> 00:21:40.333
that leads me to a question.

00:21:40.333 --> 00:21:41.700
You were talking about the,

00:21:41.700 --> 00:21:46.567
in television you really have time
to develop the sound of a show.

00:21:46.567 --> 00:21:49.333
Can you talk a little bit about
how the Battlestar music developed?

00:21:49.333 --> 00:21:49.900
Bear: Yeah.

00:21:49.900 --> 00:21:52.567
Raya: From your beginnings in
season one to the stuff in season four.

00:21:52.567 --> 00:21:52.934
Bear: Well, like I said—

00:21:52.934 --> 00:21:54.100
Raya: There’s some
really unique narrative stuff.

00:21:54.100 --> 00:21:57.433
Bear: Yeah. The show,
the music went through a lot of changes,

00:21:57.433 --> 00:22:01.967
which is something that I think
is unusual for television or,

00:22:01.967 --> 00:22:05.934
or it’s unusual for what people think
of as typical television scoring.

00:22:05.934 --> 00:22:08.834
The idea, I think, of TV scoring is that

00:22:08.834 --> 00:22:13.834
I think of the pinnacle and also
the pinnacle of functional TV music

00:22:13.834 --> 00:22:15.600
was something like Seinfeld, right,

00:22:15.600 --> 00:22:17.700
where you can hear that slap bass sound,

00:22:17.700 --> 00:22:19.333
yeah you, can you give us an example?

00:22:19.333 --> 00:22:20.400
Raya: [making sounds]

00:22:20.400 --> 00:22:21.233
Bear: There you go. [laughter]

00:22:21.233 --> 00:22:23.500
Alright. And you know exactly
what show you’re watching,

00:22:23.500 --> 00:22:24.233
there’s no question,

00:22:24.233 --> 00:22:29.467
it’s doing exactly what it needs to
do to get us from point B to point C.

00:22:29.467 --> 00:22:34.166
With Battlestar it needed a much
more cinematic and dramatic approach,

00:22:34.166 --> 00:22:40.333
but they also didn’t want what they felt
was a cinematic typical sci-fi opera score.

00:22:40.333 --> 00:22:41.734
So they said,

00:22:41.734 --> 00:22:43.900
they said, “no themes” in the beginning.

00:22:43.900 --> 00:22:48.567
So I go, “Okay. No themes.”

00:22:48.567 --> 00:22:50.166
And yet in the first episode that I did,

00:22:50.166 --> 00:22:54.500
I wrote this little thing when,

00:22:54.500 --> 00:22:58.033
when Boomer and Helo are down on
the planet I had this little thing,

00:22:58.033 --> 00:22:58.700
I remember it—

00:22:58.700 --> 00:23:06.133
♪ [playing pensive piano]

00:23:06.133 --> 00:23:07.266
I’m not gonna win any awards for that,

00:23:07.266 --> 00:23:14.467
but it’s a little germ of an idea that
I used whenever Helo and Boomer were on,

00:23:14.467 --> 00:23:16.367
were on Caprica.

00:23:16.367 --> 00:23:20.333
And then in the second episode
we went back to Caprica

00:23:20.333 --> 00:23:22.867
to follow that story line more and I thought,

00:23:22.867 --> 00:23:24.900
“Well, why should I write
a new little melody,

00:23:24.900 --> 00:23:26.500
I’ll just use that one.”

00:23:26.500 --> 00:23:28.100
But that’s a theme now.
[laughter]

00:23:28.100 --> 00:23:31.567
And especially at this point when
I’m fearing for my job, I thought,

00:23:31.567 --> 00:23:36.066
“If I tell them I’m doing this,
then I’m gonna get fired.”

00:23:36.066 --> 00:23:39.734
So I didn’t tell them and used that again.

00:23:39.734 --> 00:23:42.533
And then there was a little,

00:23:42.533 --> 00:23:44.900
there was a, in episode
four of season one

00:23:44.900 --> 00:23:49.233
I should stay at the piano –
there was a theme for Kara—

00:23:49.233 --> 00:23:54.066
♪ [playing piano]

00:23:54.066 --> 00:23:59.266
And that came back in episode,

00:23:59.266 --> 00:24:01.667
it was in episode four and then
it came back in episode five

00:24:01.667 --> 00:24:04.967
and then the next couple
of scenes with Kara,

00:24:04.967 --> 00:24:06.633
I had a chance to use it again

00:24:06.633 --> 00:24:09.767
and it was clearly a theme,
but I was just,

00:24:09.767 --> 00:24:11.533
I was afraid to tell anybody.
[laughter]

00:24:11.533 --> 00:24:13.400
And then in episode eight,

00:24:13.400 --> 00:24:16.033
so in episode eight, which
is “Flesh and bone,”

00:24:16.033 --> 00:24:18.900
that episode to me is a pivotal one

00:24:18.900 --> 00:24:23.066
because it begins what became a,

00:24:23.066 --> 00:24:25.734
a unique trait to Battlestar
which is our characters,

00:24:25.734 --> 00:24:29.300
all of our characters become
repulsive in one way or another.

00:24:29.300 --> 00:24:34.033
All of our characters do something
that makes us question whether they’re,

00:24:34.033 --> 00:24:35.500
they’re doing the right thing or not.

00:24:35.500 --> 00:24:41.266
And in this particular episode Kara Thrace
starts torturing Leoben,

00:24:41.266 --> 00:24:46.533
and of course this also sets in motion
the end of her whole story line

00:24:46.533 --> 00:24:48.734
and her relationship with Leoben
and all these things.

00:24:48.734 --> 00:24:52.166
But I don’t think, I’m not sure
the writers knew all of that ahead.

00:24:52.166 --> 00:24:53.667
They certainly didn’t tell me if they did.

00:24:53.667 --> 00:24:58.667
But in that episode I thought, “Well,
if this is the triumphant Kara—

00:24:58.667 --> 00:25:01.166
♪ [playing piano]

00:25:01.166 --> 00:25:04.233
then Film Score 101 says,
says to just make it minor—

00:25:04.233 --> 00:25:07.367
♪ [playing piano]

00:25:07.367 --> 00:25:11.400
and then you have moody, dark—

00:25:11.400 --> 00:25:14.000
conflicted Kara.
[laughter]

00:25:14.000 --> 00:25:17.400
But then the producers might feel
it’s a theme. And— [laughter]

00:25:17.400 --> 00:25:19.967
I would get fired.
[laughter]

00:25:19.967 --> 00:25:25.000
So I did it anyway,
and I didn’t get fired.

00:25:25.000 --> 00:25:27.066
And so by about the,

00:25:27.066 --> 00:25:31.700
so now at the end of season one in episode
ten which is called “The hand of God”,

00:25:31.700 --> 00:25:34.600
I was spotting with,
with one of the producers

00:25:34.600 --> 00:25:38.734
and there is a scene there where
Helo and Boomer are hiding out—

00:25:38.734 --> 00:25:41.467
there is this whole story line
throughout that season—

00:25:41.467 --> 00:25:44.800
and every episode I’m playing
a little Boomer theme.

00:25:44.800 --> 00:25:47.400
And the producers look at
that scene and he’s like,

00:25:47.400 --> 00:25:51.967
“You know having trouble,
this one’s not quite working,

00:25:51.967 --> 00:25:53.633
something’s not connecting,

00:25:53.633 --> 00:25:56.033
can we, can we use that
Boomer theme that you wrote.

00:25:56.033 --> 00:25:59.467
Can we use a little Boomer theme there?”
I was like, [laughter]

00:25:59.467 --> 00:26:03.367
“Um, good idea boss.
Yeah. Boomer theme.”

00:26:03.367 --> 00:26:06.633
And at that point I thought, “Okay.”

00:26:06.633 --> 00:26:10.200
But it was a, that was a big sort
of moment for me when I realized,

00:26:10.200 --> 00:26:14.500
“Okay. They get it that themes can be subtle.

00:26:14.500 --> 00:26:16.000
Themes can be a color.

00:26:16.000 --> 00:26:18.233
Themes can be a couple of notes.”

00:26:18.233 --> 00:26:24.433
I think that to a sci-fi audience,

00:26:24.433 --> 00:26:26.233
well, pre-Battlestar perhaps,

00:26:26.233 --> 00:26:29.767
the word theme means Luke staring off
into the twin sunsets

00:26:29.767 --> 00:26:33.734
and the french horn is playing “THE THEME”
and anything less than that,

00:26:33.734 --> 00:26:36.467
and I love that stuff,

00:26:36.467 --> 00:26:37.734
but it would have sunk Battlestar.

00:26:37.734 --> 00:26:42.600
That kind of approach in early Battlestar
would have, would have been,

00:26:42.600 --> 00:26:45.100
I think just, I don’t know.

00:26:45.100 --> 00:26:47.000
It wouldn’t have been,
it wouldn’t have been right.

00:26:47.000 --> 00:26:49.333
But I had a highly thematic approach.

00:26:49.333 --> 00:26:51.100
I was doing the same thing
that Williams was doing,

00:26:51.100 --> 00:26:54.867
I was just doing it with
different musical tools.

00:26:54.867 --> 00:26:56.600
As that, once I knew that was okay,

00:26:56.600 --> 00:26:58.600
which was episode ten of season one,
and you can,

00:26:58.600 --> 00:27:01.867
you can tell in the scores the point at
which the producer used the word theme

00:27:01.867 --> 00:27:03.400
and I realize I wasn’t gonna get fired.

00:27:03.400 --> 00:27:06.100
So starting with episode ten things start to blossom.

00:27:06.100 --> 00:27:08.033
And I introduced—

00:27:08.033 --> 00:27:10.233
Raya: In what ways did
you expand your musical palette,

00:27:10.233 --> 00:27:11.400
like instrument wise.

00:27:11.400 --> 00:27:13.600
Bear: Well, I was
going to get to that.

00:27:13.600 --> 00:27:15.834
In episode ten there was a,

00:27:15.834 --> 00:27:19.400
there was a, a Gaelic element that
I introduced with this theme—

00:27:19.400 --> 00:27:40.600
♪ [playing very melodic piano]

00:27:40.600 --> 00:27:45.133
So in the texture of Battlestar
this did not fit at all.

00:27:45.133 --> 00:27:47.333
And I knew that it didn’t fit,

00:27:47.333 --> 00:27:49.433
but there was this one scene that it did fit.

00:27:49.433 --> 00:27:53.734
At the end of this episode there
was this big jubilant celebration

00:27:53.734 --> 00:27:56.300
which itself didn’t fit the tone
of the show at that point.

00:27:56.300 --> 00:27:57.433
But one of the things
I was realizing is that

00:27:57.433 --> 00:28:00.867
this show was expanding and developing
and changing.

00:28:00.867 --> 00:28:03.433
So once that was, that scene
was in there, I thought,

00:28:03.433 --> 00:28:05.700
“Well, maybe I can use that as
a theme earlier in the episode

00:28:05.700 --> 00:28:07.800
in a more emotional setting.”

00:28:07.800 --> 00:28:10.367
So I did and I didn’t get fired.

00:28:10.367 --> 00:28:14.433
So that became a theme for,

00:28:14.433 --> 00:28:17.934
for Lee and his father and then that
started coming back in season two.

00:28:17.934 --> 00:28:21.500
That start set me on this path
where now the score was beginning

00:28:21.500 --> 00:28:23.033
to expand instrumentally.

00:28:23.033 --> 00:28:26.900
And what used to be just taiko drums
and an occasional Middle Eastern woodwind

00:28:26.900 --> 00:28:28.667
and an electric fiddle,

00:28:28.667 --> 00:28:29.834
now included bagpipes.

00:28:29.834 --> 00:28:31.066
Raya: Don’t forget
the wailing chick.

00:28:31.066 --> 00:28:32.800
Bear: And the wailing chick.
[laughter]

00:28:32.800 --> 00:28:37.133
And…
[laughter] [applause]

00:28:37.133 --> 00:28:39.467
Yes. Yes.

00:28:39.467 --> 00:28:41.100
And then, so then in,

00:28:41.100 --> 00:28:43.467
in the end of season one
we added the orchestra back in

00:28:43.467 --> 00:28:48.433
which is the thing that the producers said
adamantly that they wanted no orchestra.

00:28:48.433 --> 00:28:49.567
Well, they changed their mind.

00:28:49.567 --> 00:28:51.467
And the orchestra again,

00:28:51.467 --> 00:28:53.900
it wasn’t Luke staring off
into twin sunsets,

00:28:53.900 --> 00:28:58.033
it was, it could be used in,
in more tasteful ways for Battlestar,

00:28:58.033 --> 00:29:01.767
not dogging on Williams.
I love that stuff.

00:29:01.767 --> 00:29:06.767
But when the season ended,
the score had changed dramatically.

00:29:06.767 --> 00:29:08.800
And so then in season two,

00:29:08.800 --> 00:29:11.567
it began to change right from the get go

00:29:11.567 --> 00:29:15.033
and we started adding in some
Indian sitar and some tabla.

00:29:15.033 --> 00:29:18.500
And then in the middle of season two,
about another ten episodes in,

00:29:18.500 --> 00:29:20.734
we added a rock band,
with this episode called “Pegasus.”

00:29:20.734 --> 00:29:23.800
And then the orchestral
music became more pronounced.

00:29:23.800 --> 00:29:28.033
And so now there
was a pop-rock element.

00:29:28.033 --> 00:29:30.266
We went into season three and
I changed up the taiko writing.

00:29:30.266 --> 00:29:34.867
I added a lot more authentic
Japanese percussion.

00:29:34.867 --> 00:29:36.934
Between season two and three,

00:29:36.934 --> 00:29:41.266
I did a lot of research into how
Japanese music uses taiko drums

00:29:41.266 --> 00:29:45.333
and that, on the soundtrack album there’s
this track called “Storming New Caprica”

00:29:45.333 --> 00:29:47.100
which sounds different.

00:29:47.100 --> 00:29:50.433
I mean you can just tell it sounds
different than season one and two.

00:29:50.433 --> 00:29:53.000
And the bagpipes are still being
used in these episodes

00:29:53.000 --> 00:29:56.633
and you get to season three,
the end of season three,

00:29:56.633 --> 00:30:02.100
with “All along the watchtower” which was
a weird enough inclusion- on its own-

00:30:02.100 --> 00:30:03.900
Raya: But you want to tell
them how that came to be at all or—

00:30:03.900 --> 00:30:05.967
kind of a little synopsis.

00:30:05.967 --> 00:30:07.800
Bear: Well, the interesting
thing is all of these things,

00:30:07.800 --> 00:30:10.700
I wanna stress I’m not just throwing
these in because I got bored.

00:30:10.700 --> 00:30:11.834
Quite the contrary.

00:30:11.834 --> 00:30:15.900
Most of the time, as a composer
if you were working on a show

00:30:15.900 --> 00:30:18.567
that is in one language and
you just come in and you’re like,

00:30:18.567 --> 00:30:22.533
“Hey, I wanna do some bagpipes in
this episode,” you’re gonna get fired.

00:30:22.533 --> 00:30:25.367
It was something that
the producers encouraged

00:30:25.367 --> 00:30:27.367
and in many ways forced me to do.

00:30:27.367 --> 00:30:30.300
Because the writing evolved,
the acting evolved,

00:30:30.300 --> 00:30:34.033
the characters changed so much;
Kara Thrace is a perfect example.

00:30:34.033 --> 00:30:36.233
Her opening theme which I played you,

00:30:36.233 --> 00:30:40.500
was rather warm and triumphant and
then I created a dark version of it.

00:30:40.500 --> 00:30:43.767
Well, in season three we learned
all about this special destiny

00:30:43.767 --> 00:30:46.433
that she might have, so I wrote
a theme for that.

00:30:46.433 --> 00:30:51.500
And then later in season three
we learned about this relationship

00:30:51.500 --> 00:30:54.467
that she has with Lee and that
got expanded on dramatically.

00:30:54.467 --> 00:30:57.700
None of these other themes would
work and I wrote a theme for that.

00:30:57.700 --> 00:31:00.767
And Baltar was another character
that had multiple themes

00:31:00.767 --> 00:31:04.100
for their different personalities and
one of the things that I realized is that

00:31:04.100 --> 00:31:06.133
these people are not archetypes.

00:31:06.133 --> 00:31:10.300
You can’t write one theme that
encapsulates everything about them.

00:31:10.300 --> 00:31:12.433
And if you think about
your own personality,

00:31:12.433 --> 00:31:13.700
as much as we’d like to think,

00:31:13.700 --> 00:31:16.000
“Well, if I’m the hero of my movie,
I’d have the hero theme.”

00:31:16.000 --> 00:31:18.567
Well, there’s days when your cranky
and you have to have a cranky theme.

00:31:18.567 --> 00:31:23.166
I mean people are complicated,
multi-faceted individuals

00:31:23.166 --> 00:31:28.834
and Battlestar is a perfect
example of every character being like this.

00:31:28.834 --> 00:31:32.533
So I was forced to expand
greatly as this show went on.

00:31:32.533 --> 00:31:36.900
And “Watchtower” came along—

00:31:36.900 --> 00:31:39.867
this was an idea that Ron Moore
had in season one.

00:31:39.867 --> 00:31:45.266
He wanted the ending of season one
to be Baltar in his dream

00:31:45.266 --> 00:31:48.767
walking into the symphony hall and there’s
somebody playing “All along the watchtower”

00:31:48.767 --> 00:31:50.867
and the writer’s like, 
“Dude, no way.” [laughter]

00:31:50.867 --> 00:31:54.200
So, and then in season two we wanted to
bring it back and the writers were like,

00:31:54.200 --> 00:31:55.300
“No way.”

00:31:55.300 --> 00:31:59.100
In season three finally I think he came
up with the reason to use it.

00:31:59.100 --> 00:32:00.633
And they go, “Well, okay.”

00:32:00.633 --> 00:32:02.033
And—

00:32:02.033 --> 00:32:03.700
Raya: What, what was
your first response when you—

00:32:03.700 --> 00:32:04.900
Bear: I thought he was nuts.

00:32:04.900 --> 00:32:05.734
I thought it was—
[laughter]

00:32:05.734 --> 00:32:06.567
I thought it was the end of the show.

00:32:06.567 --> 00:32:07.934
Honestly, I thought it
was the end of the show.

00:32:07.934 --> 00:32:10.300
Because I didn’t know
how it was gonna be used.

00:32:10.300 --> 00:32:12.567
I didn’t see the episode, I
also hadn’t read the script.

00:32:12.567 --> 00:32:14.567
All I got a phone call was producer going,

00:32:14.567 --> 00:32:17.600
“Dude, Ron wants you to do an
All Along The Watchtower.”

00:32:17.600 --> 00:32:20.266
I was just like, “Good-bye.”
[laughter]

00:32:20.266 --> 00:32:22.233
But the more I thought about it,
I thought,

00:32:22.233 --> 00:32:24.333
“Well, there might be some potential here.”

00:32:24.333 --> 00:32:26.100
Raya: There might
be some way… out of here?

00:32:26.100 --> 00:32:28.467
Bear: Yes. [laughter]

00:32:28.467 --> 00:32:31.867
That was the second thing I thought.
[laughter]

00:32:31.867 --> 00:32:35.200
Well, you know, I had an idea and I thought,
“Well, I’ll try this.”

00:32:35.200 --> 00:32:36.834
I had an idea to do—

00:32:36.834 --> 00:32:38.767
we had introduced taiko drums,

00:32:38.767 --> 00:32:42.800
we’d introduced Middle Eastern music,
we’d introduced African music,

00:32:42.800 --> 00:32:45.033
heavy metal had snuck into the score in an
episode called “Black market,”

00:32:45.033 --> 00:32:49.166
which was just this source piece that I’d
done because I wanted to a heavy metal song

00:32:49.166 --> 00:32:51.100
but there it was, on the 
season two soundtrack,

00:32:51.100 --> 00:32:52.400
and it was in the fabric of the show.

00:32:52.400 --> 00:32:54.934
So I thought, “Well, I’ll try
to do the version of this,

00:32:54.934 --> 00:32:57.400
of Watchtower that I think would be cool.

00:32:57.400 --> 00:32:58.867
And then I can at least tell everybody that

00:32:58.867 --> 00:33:01.667
there was a cool version at one point
in the past.”

00:33:01.667 --> 00:33:03.166
’Cause I was sure that this wouldn’t fly.

00:33:03.166 --> 00:33:05.333
So I did this, what I called,

00:33:05.333 --> 00:33:08.567
George Harrison sits in with
Rage Against The Machine,

00:33:08.567 --> 00:33:12.667
kind of Indian, Middle Eastern version
of “All along the watchtower.”

00:33:12.667 --> 00:33:14.433
So I threw it together – a demo.

00:33:14.433 --> 00:33:17.734
My brother stepped off a plane
and he recorded the demo vocals

00:33:17.734 --> 00:33:19.600
and I sent it to Ron
and I was just like,

00:33:19.600 --> 00:33:22.166
“Okay. Well, that will be the end of this.”

00:33:22.166 --> 00:33:26.767
And Ron writes back and he’s like,
“Oh, it’s great.” [laughter]

00:33:26.767 --> 00:33:28.400
And it was, that was it.

00:33:28.400 --> 00:33:31.233
“No, I can totally see that fitting
with the action in the episode.”

00:33:31.233 --> 00:33:32.867
And I was like, “There’s
action in the episode?”

00:33:32.867 --> 00:33:35.133
I didn’t even know.

00:33:35.133 --> 00:33:37.433
And ultimately the version that
you hear on the album

00:33:37.433 --> 00:33:40.066
and in the show is almost identical;

00:33:40.066 --> 00:33:42.400
some of the tracks are from the demo.

00:33:42.400 --> 00:33:46.633
It’s exactly what my initial vision
was, and I think part of that is,

00:33:46.633 --> 00:33:52.700
is thanks to Ron letting me do
whatever I wanted; he gave me no input.

00:33:52.700 --> 00:33:56.100
I mean it was literally the first time
that the producer said nothing to me.

00:33:56.100 --> 00:33:58.633
Before I wrote it, I caught him
in the hallway and I said,

00:33:58.633 --> 00:34:00.166
“Ron, dude, what, what do you want me to do?

00:34:00.166 --> 00:34:01.367
It is, should it sound like Bob Dylan?

00:34:01.367 --> 00:34:02.567
Should it sound like Jimi Hendrix?”

00:34:02.567 --> 00:34:04.533
And he goes,
“Make it sound like Battlestar.”

00:34:04.533 --> 00:34:06.200
And he walked away.
[laughter]

00:34:06.200 --> 00:34:08.433
Like this was easy,
you know? [laughter]

00:34:08.433 --> 00:34:14.200
And I also think that
the network had faith in Ron.

00:34:14.200 --> 00:34:18.300
I personally believe that they
weren’t sure what to make of it.

00:34:18.300 --> 00:34:21.900
I think it was something
that was extremely daring,

00:34:21.900 --> 00:34:24.734
I mean whether you liked it or not,
it was extremely daring.

00:34:24.734 --> 00:34:28.633
And that blasted open the doors
in season four

00:34:28.633 --> 00:34:33.000
where now the music is something
the characters hear;

00:34:33.000 --> 00:34:36.533
the themes are melodies they’re aware of;

00:34:36.533 --> 00:34:42.500
and the music became a part
of the show in a way that

00:34:42.500 --> 00:34:46.100
I can’t think of another film or television
show that did it in this exact way.

00:34:46.100 --> 00:34:48.100
And the writers began calling me.

00:34:48.100 --> 00:34:49.266
I was on set.

00:34:49.266 --> 00:34:51.133
I was involved in the scripts—

00:34:51.133 --> 00:34:52.667
Raya: It got kind of
meta eventually,

00:34:52.667 --> 00:34:56.266
because first it was kinda like you’re
following the narrative of the show—

00:34:56.266 --> 00:34:58.367
And then, and what’s,
what’s the name of the episode—

00:34:58.367 --> 00:35:00.633
Bear: Well, “Someone to watch
over me” was one of the first ones.

00:35:00.633 --> 00:35:02.800
Raya: Yeah, suddenly
the show started following you.

00:35:02.800 --> 00:35:03.200
Bear: Exactly.

00:35:03.200 --> 00:35:07.166
The character in that named Slick,
who’s this piano player,

00:35:07.166 --> 00:35:08.967
every time he’s talking about music,

00:35:08.967 --> 00:35:13.667
what he’s saying is what I was saying
when I was writing

00:35:13.667 --> 00:35:17.100
that season’s mid-season cliffhanger
in an episode called “Revelations.”

00:35:17.100 --> 00:35:18.000
So you’ve got to think about this;

00:35:18.000 --> 00:35:20.600
I’m writing, I’m struggling
to write this cue

00:35:20.600 --> 00:35:22.567
that was one of the toughest cues
I’d ever written,

00:35:22.567 --> 00:35:24.767
and the writers called me
up and they’re like,

00:35:24.767 --> 00:35:25.734
“Can we take a minute of your time?

00:35:25.734 --> 00:35:27.300
We got this character, a composer;

00:35:27.300 --> 00:35:29.367
he’s writing a cue;
he’s having trouble with it.

00:35:29.367 --> 00:35:31.367
What is that like?”
And I was just like— [laughter]

00:35:31.367 --> 00:35:33.000
“Dammit.”
[laughter]

00:35:33.000 --> 00:35:34.533
So like it was, it was perfect.

00:35:34.533 --> 00:35:36.266
I mean literally David Weddle
was like,

00:35:36.266 --> 00:35:36.967
“Hang on.

00:35:36.967 --> 00:35:39.567
Don’t, don’t figure it out,
don’t figure it out,

00:35:39.567 --> 00:35:41.667
let me get a pencil,
we’ll write this down.” [laughter]

00:35:41.667 --> 00:35:44.533
So that’s exact,
it was me, that was me,

00:35:44.533 --> 00:35:47.433
what I was going through to write this,
this other cue.

00:35:47.433 --> 00:35:48.600
Raya: And in fact you got
so close that

00:35:48.600 --> 00:35:50.000
you went up to the set for that one.

00:35:50.000 --> 00:35:51.233
Bear: Yeah, I was,
I was on set

00:35:51.233 --> 00:35:54.033
and I worked with the actors,
I worked with Katee and Roark,

00:35:54.033 --> 00:35:56.400
I taught them the piano parts.

00:35:56.400 --> 00:35:58.367
Roark is an excellent pianist

00:35:58.367 --> 00:36:01.233
and as he was actually cast
so that he could play my music.

00:36:01.233 --> 00:36:03.700
They only auditioned
people that could play piano.

00:36:03.700 --> 00:36:09.233
And – fun trivia – they actually
auditioned me for this. [laughter]

00:36:09.233 --> 00:36:12.467
Needless to say, my talents are
clearly on the compositional side.

00:36:12.467 --> 00:36:14.266
[laughter]

00:36:14.266 --> 00:36:15.066
But—

00:36:15.066 --> 00:36:16.066
Raya: But you went to
the audition.

00:36:16.066 --> 00:36:17.834
Bear: I did. I did.

00:36:17.834 --> 00:36:21.300
It was, yeah.
[laughter]

00:36:21.300 --> 00:36:25.166
So, and then even in the last episode,
I will keep this,

00:36:25.166 --> 00:36:27.500
is there anyone here who hasn’t seen
the last episode? Raise your hand.

00:36:27.500 --> 00:36:28.633
It’s okay. Okay.

00:36:28.633 --> 00:36:30.834
I just, alright.
I won’t spoil it.

00:36:30.834 --> 00:36:35.033
In the last episode,
something happens, yeah.

00:36:35.033 --> 00:36:36.567
And there, there are—

00:36:36.567 --> 00:36:39.166
And there are, there are,
there are coordinates involved.

00:36:39.166 --> 00:36:43.834
And these are coordinates that,
that I came up with.

00:36:43.834 --> 00:36:46.867
Actually Ron called me and was like,
“Hey, we need a way to,

00:36:46.867 --> 00:36:50.500
to communicate this idea that the music
and the coordinates are tied together.”

00:36:50.500 --> 00:36:53.900
And actually I worked with Kevin Grazier,
the science advisor, and I was like,

00:36:53.900 --> 00:36:59.934
“Well, tell me how many coordinates, 
how many digits do we need?”

00:36:59.934 --> 00:37:03.133
And he would, he’s, you guys
probably know better than I do,

00:37:03.133 --> 00:37:07.734
it was, he needed 12 digits
to create this set of coordinates.

00:37:07.734 --> 00:37:14.166
And by coincidence the theme that
I was messing around with at the time

00:37:14.166 --> 00:37:15.133
had 12 notes.

00:37:15.133 --> 00:37:19.867
♪ [playing piano]

00:37:19.867 --> 00:37:21.200
And then returning to one is 13.

00:37:21.200 --> 00:37:22.066
♪ [plays one note on piano]

00:37:22.066 --> 00:37:27.867
For the thirteenth colony. Ooh. 
[laughter] Naah, I’m making that up.

00:37:27.867 --> 00:37:28.700
Yeah, that was a coincidence.

00:37:28.700 --> 00:37:31.934
But anyway, it was a happy coincidence
and then I thought, “okay”—

00:37:31.934 --> 00:37:36.567
and I devised a number of different
ways we could generate these pitches

00:37:36.567 --> 00:37:44.100
and I came up with complex grids of
intervals and different scaling,

00:37:44.100 --> 00:37:46.600
ways of numbering a scale
to create these numbers.

00:37:46.600 --> 00:37:50.667
And I said to the writers, “Okay, well
how long is the scene that we have to explain this.

