you know, just down and down and down.

00:53:51.233 --> 00:53:55.300
And you don’t notice it because
it’s over the course of 44 minutes,

00:53:55.300 --> 00:53:57.567
but I think that subconsciously things
like that—

00:53:57.567 --> 00:54:00.333
that and the way that the rhythm
is just getting faster and faster,

00:54:00.333 --> 00:54:02.600
it does create this feeling that

00:54:02.600 --> 00:54:05.166
you’re kind of spiraling out
of control towards something.

00:54:05.166 --> 00:54:07.333
So that can be a really powerful tool,

00:54:07.333 --> 00:54:10.633
and obviously when you’re thinking
in terms of drums

00:54:10.633 --> 00:54:14.033
and a lot of my music is very percussion
heavy, rhythm is—

00:54:14.033 --> 00:54:17.000
you got to have a cool groove.

00:54:19.233 --> 00:54:22.667
Member of the audience: Do you have a dream of something you
want to do that you haven’t been able to do?

00:54:22.667 --> 00:54:23.967
And if so, what is that?

00:54:23.967 --> 00:54:28.633
Bear: Boy, I don’t know.
I got to score a Terminator TV show,

00:54:28.633 --> 00:54:32.433
and, yeah, do an 8-bit thing.

00:54:32.433 --> 00:54:33.000
I don’t know.

00:54:33.000 --> 00:54:39.066
I mean, my dream is keep writing music and
continuing to do what I love, you know.

00:54:39.066 --> 00:54:42.066
And the fact that people are
out there listening to it

00:54:42.066 --> 00:54:44.066
is wonderful and icing on the cake.

00:54:44.066 --> 00:54:46.367
But I mean like the fact that I can keep—

00:54:46.367 --> 00:54:51.834
just keep writing music is
my dream, you know, for sure.

00:54:51.834 --> 00:54:54.200
Member of the audience: How did you pick the Gayatri Mantra
for the title, and more generally,

00:54:54.200 --> 00:54:56.700
how do you come up with these lyrics in all
these different languages?

00:54:56.700 --> 00:54:59.567
Bear: Well, it’s interesting
the mantra came from Eddie Olmos.

00:54:59.567 --> 00:55:02.033
Eddie played this on the set

00:55:02.033 --> 00:55:03.934
so it was something that even
before any composer was hired

00:55:03.934 --> 00:55:10.600
was part of the Battlestar Galactica
universe, you know, in an indirect way.

00:55:10.600 --> 00:55:13.367
And what was the other question?
It was about—

00:55:13.367 --> 00:55:13.767
Member of the audience: Lyrics.

00:55:13.767 --> 00:55:15.433
Bear: Oh, lyrics.
Thank you.

00:55:15.433 --> 00:55:17.066
Lyrics are interesting.

00:55:17.066 --> 00:55:19.767
I didn’t write any lyrics for
the first couple of tunes.

00:55:19.767 --> 00:55:23.367
The first time I wrote lyrics for
the show was for an Italian opera scene

00:55:23.367 --> 00:55:25.500
in this comedic moment.

00:55:25.500 --> 00:55:29.333
And I wrote these lyrics
that were sort of a parody.

00:55:29.333 --> 00:55:32.100
I mean, they were like very
operatic, angsty lyrics.

00:55:32.100 --> 00:55:35.333
“Woe unto your Cylon heart,
my girlfriend is a toaster,

00:55:35.333 --> 00:55:37.867
the spine glows red,” and you know,
blah blah blah.

00:55:37.867 --> 00:55:40.467
And it’s clear as day,
I mean it’s in Italian

00:55:40.467 --> 00:55:43.533
but it’s like, if you speak Italian,
there’s no dialogue obscuring it.

00:55:43.533 --> 00:55:46.800
And at the dub where the producers
heard it for the first time,

00:55:46.800 --> 00:55:48.867
they were like, dude,
this music is really beautiful.

00:55:48.867 --> 00:55:49.867
What are those lyrics, by the way?

00:55:49.867 --> 00:55:52.900
And I was like, oh, I don’t
have them on me – I’m sorry.

00:55:52.900 --> 00:55:54.867
[laughter] Can I – I’ll
show them to you tomorrow.

00:55:54.867 --> 00:55:58.500
Knowing that we were shipping
that night and—

00:55:58.500 --> 00:56:01.600
cause, you know, I didn’t want them
to get cold feet.

00:56:01.600 --> 00:56:05.900
And then after I started
approaching the lyrics more seriously.

00:56:05.900 --> 00:56:09.367
In season three, I got to write
the tune that was in Armenian,

00:56:09.367 --> 00:56:15.400
and comment on things that I was feeling.

00:56:15.400 --> 00:56:20.266
And write a song that I wanted to write,
but also that commented on the—

00:56:20.266 --> 00:56:21.333
on the events of the episode.

00:56:21.333 --> 00:56:25.700
And it was great because I could always
hide in another, you know, language.

00:56:25.700 --> 00:56:27.133
And I always get kind of—

00:56:27.133 --> 00:56:29.500
people sometimes they ask, dude,
is that outer space language

00:56:29.500 --> 00:56:31.266
that they’re singing in?

00:56:31.266 --> 00:56:32.633
And I was like, no way.

00:56:32.633 --> 00:56:35.033
Like, I go out of my way
to write these lyrics

00:56:35.033 --> 00:56:37.033
and to translate them and to
have them sung authentically.

00:56:37.033 --> 00:56:40.133
That’s something – that’s a layer that
I think adds a lot of authenticity.

00:56:40.133 --> 00:56:43.333
I love the Ewok song.
I’m not dogging on that.

00:56:43.333 --> 00:56:48.266
But I think for Battlestar, it
wouldn’t have been appropriate.

00:56:48.266 --> 00:56:51.433
Member of the audience: Have you ever been like
doing the music for a project

00:56:51.433 --> 00:56:54.600
and you were like “This is
the worst TV show ever.”

00:56:54.600 --> 00:56:57.033
Bear: No, generally
I don’t take those on.

00:56:57.033 --> 00:56:59.600
If it’s truly the worst TV show ever.

00:56:59.600 --> 00:57:01.567
There are plenty of times, though,

00:57:01.567 --> 00:57:05.000
when, you know, you’re working on something that

00:57:05.000 --> 00:57:07.767
you have to do your best on
whether you believe in it or not.

00:57:07.767 --> 00:57:10.000
You know, I mean, that’s part of
your job. You’re a craftsman,

00:57:10.000 --> 00:57:13.600
and sometimes I think about it
like sometimes I’m a guy

00:57:13.600 --> 00:57:16.200
who gets to, you know,
paint the painting.

00:57:16.200 --> 00:57:19.400
Other times, I’m a guy who
comes in to fix your leaky pipe.

00:57:19.400 --> 00:57:22.700
And this thing isn’t working,
and you got to fix it.

00:57:22.700 --> 00:57:26.133
And the music can make things better
so sometimes it—

00:57:26.133 --> 00:57:27.400
you just got to wear different hats

00:57:27.400 --> 00:57:30.233
and it depends on the quality
of what you’re working on.

00:57:30.233 --> 00:57:31.066
Thankfully on Battlestar,

00:57:31.066 --> 00:57:37.300
most of the time, I was the painter
and not the plumber. You know.

00:57:37.300 --> 00:57:40.200
Member of the audience: I appreciate your defense of
the Yub Dub song, by the way.

00:57:40.200 --> 00:57:42.200
Bear: Totally, dude.
I miss it.

00:57:42.200 --> 00:57:48.533
Member of the audience: I like the fact that Battlestar
Galactica got to have a theme.

00:57:48.533 --> 00:57:49.166
Bear: Yeah.

00:57:49.166 --> 00:57:54.033
Member of the audience: And everyone’s familiar with
television theme songs or whatever.

00:57:54.033 --> 00:57:57.500
Is… Are people in your position,
is the industry,

00:57:57.500 --> 00:58:03.100
do they have to defend the idea of
having an opening theme now with,

00:58:03.100 --> 00:58:05.333
you know, Dick Wolf, with,
you know, two notes

00:58:05.333 --> 00:58:08.266
and some of these shows that are
in prime time who don’t get one?

00:58:08.266 --> 00:58:09.066
Bear: Can we show
the Human Target main theme?

00:58:09.066 --> 00:58:11.100
Let me show you a main theme I just did.

00:58:11.100 --> 00:58:13.667
And then I’ll answer that question.

00:58:14.100 --> 00:58:47.433
♪ [music playing]

00:58:48.867 --> 00:58:52.266
Bear: So there is an example
of not having to fight for the theme.

00:58:52.266 --> 00:58:54.400
I mean, clearly the guys that produce
this show

00:58:54.400 --> 00:58:59.333
wanted a strong main title theme with
beautiful visuals and a memorable,

00:58:59.333 --> 00:59:00.367
melodic theme.

00:59:00.367 --> 00:59:05.033
And it is something that,
if the producers don’t want it,

00:59:05.033 --> 00:59:07.467
you know, as a composer,
you can’t change their minds.

00:59:07.467 --> 00:59:09.600
But I think that is coming back.

00:59:09.600 --> 00:59:14.266
Getting to do a theme song like that,
with a full orchestra at my disposal,

00:59:14.266 --> 00:59:18.300
and getting to write a melody like that,
is pretty unusual.

00:59:18.300 --> 00:59:21.967
And I’d love for it to become more usual,
and I think not coincidentally,

00:59:21.967 --> 00:59:25.066
the guy that hired me to do this show
is a big fan of Battlestar,

00:59:25.066 --> 00:59:28.266
and that’s one of the reasons I got the
job is he heard what I doing in Battlestar

00:59:28.266 --> 00:59:31.400
and wanted to bring that kind
of energy to his show.

00:59:31.400 --> 00:59:33.433
So I’d love to be able to
do more of that.

00:59:33.433 --> 00:59:36.166
But for a while there it
was a dying art, for sure.

00:59:36.166 --> 00:59:38.000
Raya: Can I make a special request?

00:59:38.000 --> 00:59:39.000
Bear: What’s that?

00:59:39.000 --> 00:59:40.567
Raya: Can you play the Sarah Connor theme?
’Cause it’s one of my favorites?

00:59:40.567 --> 00:59:43.500
Bear: I don’t have it.
I only have the Samson and Delilah theme.

00:59:43.500 --> 00:59:44.800
Hang on.

00:59:44.800 --> 00:59:46.000
Fiancée asks.

00:59:51.166 --> 01:00:20.100
♪ [playing the Sarah Connor theme on the piano]

01:00:20.100 --> 01:00:22.166
Bear: I miss that show.

01:00:22.166 --> 01:00:23.867
Okay.

01:00:23.867 --> 01:00:25.500
Any other questions?

01:00:25.500 --> 01:00:26.700
Member of the audience: Yeah, actually that’s a good segue.

01:00:26.700 --> 01:00:29.033
I was going to ask about
Sarah Connor Chronicles,

01:00:29.033 --> 01:00:32.767
and you did that show for two seasons,
which if I’m not mistaken,

01:00:32.767 --> 01:00:36.066
which is the second longest run
you’ve had on a show.

01:00:36.066 --> 01:00:38.467
Bear: Up there.
So far.

01:00:38.467 --> 01:00:39.834
Member of the audience: So far, of course.

01:00:39.834 --> 01:00:44.567
I’m curious if you feel like you’ve had
an opportunity on that to have fun

01:00:44.567 --> 01:00:46.967
and basically explore themes.

01:00:46.967 --> 01:00:49.133
Obviously, you didn’t have
as long as on Battlestar,

01:00:49.133 --> 01:00:55.567
but do you feel like you missed
an opportunity to explore those themes

01:00:55.567 --> 01:00:58.066
and those story lines more?

01:00:58.066 --> 01:01:01.033
Bear: Well, I mean—
I think I can answer your question.

01:01:01.033 --> 01:01:05.567
Yeah, I had a very thematic score
on Terminator.

01:01:05.567 --> 01:01:07.667
We were in a very similar situation
with Battlestar,

01:01:07.667 --> 01:01:14.867
where we were coming from something that
existed already and needed to know—

01:01:14.867 --> 01:01:17.533
are we acknowledging or are
we distancing ourselves?

01:01:17.533 --> 01:01:20.333
And with Battlestar,
I could do everything

01:01:20.333 --> 01:01:22.633
except for what Stu Phillips did
on the old show.

01:01:22.633 --> 01:01:25.200
Obviously, with some disclaimer,
I could spend on hour talking about

01:01:25.200 --> 01:01:28.500
how wonderful Stu is and how wonderful
it was to bring his theme back.

01:01:28.500 --> 01:01:31.133
But it really was a special
occasion in Battlestar.

01:01:31.133 --> 01:01:35.033
Terminator was different
because we wanted to—

01:01:35.033 --> 01:01:37.533
we wanted to connect directly
to Terminator 2,

01:01:37.533 --> 01:01:39.400
and it should feel very much like a sequel.

01:01:39.400 --> 01:01:43.900
So the score needed to
kind of help ease that in.

01:01:43.900 --> 01:01:48.066
“Yeah, I know it’s Lena Headey but she’s
the same person that Linda Hamilton was.”

01:01:48.066 --> 01:01:51.700
This is the spirit of this is
very much coming out of T2.

01:01:51.700 --> 01:01:55.200
So I had that as a starting point,

01:01:55.200 --> 01:01:58.500
but I was also able to say to
the producers that the Terminator theme,

01:01:58.500 --> 01:02:03.700
I felt, from the movies, is excellent
as it is, I think of Schwarzenegger,

01:02:03.700 --> 01:02:05.000
I think of those movies.

01:02:05.000 --> 01:02:06.200
I don’t even think of the characters,

01:02:06.200 --> 01:02:09.166
like the movies themselves have become
such phenomena

01:02:09.166 --> 01:02:11.600
that it’s hard to distance
ourselves from them.

01:02:11.600 --> 01:02:14.900
So I thought I don’t think there’s
a theme that’s Sarah Connor’s theme.

01:02:14.900 --> 01:02:17.100
So can we try writing one?

01:02:17.100 --> 01:02:22.734
And they were open to exploring this
new, you know, musical universe.

01:02:22.734 --> 01:02:28.033
And I had an electric string quartet
where we were running the quartet

01:02:28.033 --> 01:02:32.900
through amplifiers and digital effects,
actually mostly analog effects,

01:02:32.900 --> 01:02:35.567
and recorded the group that way.

01:02:35.567 --> 01:02:38.667
We had big metallic percussion,
we had car parts,

01:02:38.667 --> 01:02:44.266
and brakes and anvils and hammers
and like – I mean, it was a blast.

01:02:44.266 --> 01:02:48.467
And that album is worth checking
out for some of those colors alone.

01:02:48.467 --> 01:02:51.467
Thematically, I feel like
I was just getting started.

01:02:51.467 --> 01:02:53.500
I mean, I would adore to go back.

01:02:53.500 --> 01:02:57.734
And there was some talk of
doing a straight-to-DVD movie.

01:02:57.734 --> 01:03:02.000
And I think that ultimately, it’s the just
legalities and the business of it.

01:03:02.000 --> 01:03:06.000
You know, the rights are tangled up
with a company that went Chapter 11.

01:03:06.000 --> 01:03:10.400
And so it may never happen
and that would make me sad,

01:03:10.400 --> 01:03:14.033
but I’m really happy that that album
is out there, that show is out there,

01:03:14.033 --> 01:03:17.500
and I was able to – going back to
whoever asked me about my dream,

01:03:17.500 --> 01:03:22.066
I was able to contribute something
to the Terminator universe.

01:03:22.066 --> 01:03:24.533
I’m thrilled with that, you know.

01:03:24.533 --> 01:03:26.567
Member of the audience: Thanks.
Bear: Thanks.

01:03:26.567 --> 01:03:29.133
Host: One last question?

01:03:29.133 --> 01:03:31.100
Okay.

01:03:31.100 --> 01:03:33.000
Member of the audience: For those of us who aren’t
familiar with the terminology,

01:03:33.000 --> 01:03:34.967
can you talk about what’s involved
in writing a cue

01:03:34.967 --> 01:03:38.433
and why is that more difficult than
writing just some music independently?

01:03:38.433 --> 01:03:40.400
Bear: Well, it
depends on your perspective.

01:03:40.400 --> 01:03:43.033
I don’t think it is more difficult,
personally.

01:03:43.033 --> 01:03:45.000
I think that the difference is that

01:03:45.000 --> 01:03:47.066
when you’re writing a piece
of music for yourself,

01:03:47.066 --> 01:03:51.467
you need to make yourself happy
and express yourself

01:03:51.467 --> 01:03:53.633
and figure out what you’re going to say
and how you’re going to say it

01:03:53.633 --> 01:03:55.934
and who your audience is and
how you’re going to perform it—

01:03:55.934 --> 01:03:57.934
there’s a lot of variables.

01:03:57.934 --> 01:04:02.567
And most of the time when – when
you have an idea, it’s wonderful.

01:04:02.567 --> 01:04:04.834
“I just have an idea and
it’s going to spill forth,

01:04:04.834 --> 01:04:09.000
and the audience will find it,” but a lot
of the times those things are not as easy.

01:04:09.000 --> 01:04:10.800
With scoring for picture,

01:04:10.800 --> 01:04:13.166
you know how long it’s going to be,
you know the shape,

01:04:13.166 --> 01:04:15.433
you know which characters are involved,

01:04:15.433 --> 01:04:17.333
you know the emotions you’re probably
going to want to play.

01:04:17.333 --> 01:04:21.467
And I found that I’d become very quick
at looking at a scene

01:04:21.467 --> 01:04:24.633
and in my mind almost being able
to score it instantly.

01:04:24.633 --> 01:04:25.700
I don’t know the themes.

01:04:25.700 --> 01:04:30.266
I don’t know the exact rhythms
but it’s like I can see the shape.

01:04:30.266 --> 01:04:33.233
I can see the shape that’s it like,
it’s almost like geometric.

01:04:33.233 --> 01:04:37.133
It’s gonna start this way and be
purple and kind of dark and brooding

01:04:37.133 --> 01:04:38.867
and then a rhythm comes in here

01:04:38.867 --> 01:04:41.734
when this guy says something
or when this action happens.

01:04:41.734 --> 01:04:44.233
And then a lot of the times,
I’ll just look at a scene

01:04:44.233 --> 01:04:46.767
and then I’ll see these kind of blocks,
and now I go, okay,

01:04:46.767 --> 01:04:48.033
what are my rhythms?

01:04:48.033 --> 01:04:48.900
What are the pitches?

01:04:48.900 --> 01:04:50.900
What are the melodies I’m going to use?

01:04:50.900 --> 01:04:52.467
These things are – for me,

01:04:52.467 --> 01:04:57.300
they’re relatively easy to that basic
idea of what am I going to say?

01:04:57.300 --> 01:05:00.333
And when I’m writing music on my own,
which I love to do—

01:05:00.333 --> 01:05:02.834
I’m a tough critic, you know.

01:05:02.834 --> 01:05:04.800
And that’s self-censorship kicks in.

01:05:04.800 --> 01:05:06.033
I got a cool idea.

01:05:06.033 --> 01:05:08.900
No, it’s not a cool enough idea.
Screw it.

01:05:08.900 --> 01:05:13.133
And the other thing I find useful
about scoring for TV and movies,

01:05:13.133 --> 01:05:14.233
you have a deadline.

01:05:14.233 --> 01:05:16.600
So your first idea, you
don’t have time to go back.

01:05:16.600 --> 01:05:18.667
And you’re not going to write
three drafts and pick the best one.

01:05:18.667 --> 01:05:21.533
The thing you sit down to write,
that’s what’s going on the air.

01:05:21.533 --> 01:05:23.667
So if it’s not good when you write it,

01:05:23.667 --> 01:05:27.700
you tweak it or you get the performer
to change it, or you edit it later,

01:05:27.700 --> 01:05:30.433
but it’s – it’s trained me
to become very fast.

01:05:30.433 --> 01:05:33.600
And in fact, I think of myself
creatively almost like a—

01:05:33.600 --> 01:05:38.667
I think of my creative mind the way I think
a marathon runner thinks about their body

01:05:38.667 --> 01:05:40.734
where it’s just like I’m always
training myself,

01:05:40.734 --> 01:05:42.900
and I know the days I need to
get more sleep.

01:05:42.900 --> 01:05:44.867
I know the days that I can sacrifice sleep.

01:05:44.867 --> 01:05:46.233
I know the hours that I write the best.

01:05:46.233 --> 01:05:50.367
I know the cues that I should write
in those hours, you know what I mean?

01:05:50.367 --> 01:05:54.367
If I didn’t figure all these thing out
and I was like I’m going to write some cues,

01:05:54.367 --> 01:05:55.700
it would be difficult.

01:05:55.700 --> 01:05:58.533
But I have kind of learned
how to do these things.

01:05:58.533 --> 01:06:02.200
And I mean, with Human Target
being a full orchestra now,

01:06:02.200 --> 01:06:08.667
I’m generating between 45 minutes and
55 minutes of original music a week.

01:06:08.667 --> 01:06:11.934
And in fact, today’s the first day
I haven’t written music since New Year’s.

01:06:11.934 --> 01:06:16.100
So – it’s something that
you just rely on the—

01:06:16.100 --> 01:06:18.967
the craft and the technique,
and the things you know.

01:06:18.967 --> 01:06:22.900
And when you’re doing a song for yourself,
it’s fun but all those parameters are gone.

01:06:22.900 --> 01:06:23.533
You could do anything.

01:06:23.533 --> 01:06:27.000
I find that slows me down, you know.

01:06:27.000 --> 01:06:29.900
Member of the audience: So I’m not trying to
evoke like things you hate—

01:06:29.900 --> 01:06:30.533
Bear: Oh, go for it.

01:06:30.533 --> 01:06:34.967
Member of the audience: But do you ever watch a program
or a movie or a project and you say

01:06:34.967 --> 01:06:37.367
not only could I have done it better
but I wish I had been able to that?

01:06:37.367 --> 01:06:39.400
Not necessarily hating
on the person who did it.

01:06:39.400 --> 01:06:40.333
Bear: You know it’s difficult.

01:06:40.333 --> 01:06:45.033
I mean, when I—
I have found that, again,

01:06:45.033 --> 01:06:47.000
going back to that marathon runner mentality,

01:06:47.000 --> 01:06:49.633
I can’t – I can’t shut that off.

01:06:49.633 --> 01:06:53.500
So when I go—
I’m so used to looking at picture

01:06:53.500 --> 01:06:58.633
and just constantly analyzing every facial
tic, every line of dialogue, every cut,

01:06:58.633 --> 01:06:59.867
thinking “all right, what can we do?”

01:06:59.867 --> 01:07:01.400
“What’s the best way to do this?”

01:07:01.400 --> 01:07:04.100
I can’t shut that off when
I watch anything else.

01:07:04.100 --> 01:07:06.033
So it’s very difficult for me—

01:07:06.033 --> 01:07:08.867
it’s not about thinking that
this score isn’t adequate.

01:07:08.867 --> 01:07:12.400
If anything, I just keep thinking
about what else could be done?

01:07:12.400 --> 01:07:15.100
And what I would do and I actually
have to make a conscious effort

01:07:15.100 --> 01:07:18.333
to shut that part of my brain off
to enjoy something.

01:07:18.333 --> 01:07:22.000
And admittedly, that’s
becoming very, very difficult.

01:07:22.000 --> 01:07:23.834
And I’ve been working professionally—

01:07:23.834 --> 01:07:27.266
I mean, I’ve been working under deadlines
like this for 7 or 8 years now.

01:07:27.266 --> 01:07:29.900
And I – it’s almost impossible.

01:07:29.900 --> 01:07:33.967
And should I be fortunate enough
to end up like Elmer Bernstein

01:07:33.967 --> 01:07:36.133
and do this until I’m 80,

01:07:36.133 --> 01:07:38.200
I can’t imagine that’s it’s
going to get any better,

01:07:38.200 --> 01:07:41.033
you know, just doing the condition
the same thing everyday.

01:07:41.033 --> 01:07:41.567
So it is tough.

01:07:41.567 --> 01:07:47.633
It’s harder to enjoy—
it’s harder to enjoy media in general.

01:07:47.633 --> 01:07:50.400
Somebody asked me earlier at lunch
what kind of music do you listen to?

01:07:50.400 --> 01:07:54.934
I don’t – I love music but I don’t
necessarily listen to it for fun anymore

01:07:54.934 --> 01:07:57.767
because I’m always listening to
the mixes that I’ve got to approve

01:07:57.767 --> 01:07:59.967
or listening to the cues that
I just wrote trying to figure out

01:07:59.967 --> 01:08:01.567
how I’m going to orchestrate them.

01:08:01.567 --> 01:08:06.500
So it’s a part of my life that I—
that I’ve got a new side of it.

01:08:06.500 --> 01:08:09.734
A quick tangential side story to that and
the way this has sort of changed my life.

01:08:09.734 --> 01:08:13.000
When I was growing up, the first pop band
I was into was Oingo Boingo,

01:08:13.000 --> 01:08:15.967
huge fan of Oingo Boingo.

01:08:15.967 --> 01:08:17.467
Huge fan.

01:08:17.467 --> 01:08:21.300
And now, it’s like I think,
well, am I fan of Oingo Boingo?

01:08:21.300 --> 01:08:26.266
And I am not because I work with
these guys almost every day.

01:08:26.266 --> 01:08:29.567
I’ve – me and my brother have performed
with them doing Oingo Boingo music

01:08:29.567 --> 01:08:33.100
on stage in these crazy sold-out
Halloween concerts.

01:08:33.100 --> 01:08:36.533
It’s funny, cause I go, well,
no I’m not—

01:08:36.533 --> 01:08:40.533
I still love their music, but it’s
like a different relationship that I have.

01:08:40.533 --> 01:08:44.033
And then, that’s my relationship
with music and art has changed

01:08:44.033 --> 01:08:46.600
because of my involvement in it every day.

01:08:46.600 --> 01:08:48.900
So it isn’t something I enjoy.

01:08:48.900 --> 01:08:52.767
I’m sure if any of you guys use
another computer program

01:08:52.767 --> 01:08:56.166
or look at another search engine or another
phone or something you – you’re like,

01:08:56.166 --> 01:08:58.433
can you just enjoy on its own?
Oh, this is awesome.

01:08:58.433 --> 01:09:02.000
I mean, you’re probably all thinking,
you know, the stuff you think everyday.

01:09:02.000 --> 01:09:05.133
[laughter]

01:09:05.133 --> 01:09:08.433
Anyway, it’s – it’s a lot of fun.

01:09:08.433 --> 01:09:14.233
It’s – you know, a wonderful dream come
true for me to be able to do this, so.

01:09:16.300 --> 01:09:19.400
Bear: On the way, as we’re walking
out, I want to show the “Apocalypse” video.

01:09:19.400 --> 01:09:21.367
I think that’s pretty awesome.

